<br>
I agree that selling CV to the masses may be difficult but so what.  It's not really that complicated, it's just something that can't be broken down into cute little sound bites.  As a voter you don't have to understand the math behind Cloneproof Schwartz Sequential Dropping (though it's not to bad either.)  You just have to know the basics of how it works.  Kinda like using a computer, you don't have to know how to program the damn things, just how to make them do what you want.  The ballots themselves are easy to understand, just rank your candidates as far as you want to go, the computers do the tabulation.  I think if the momentum behind IRV was shifted to CV we'd be in good shape as far as changing the system goes.  Because really CV is no more complicated than IRV, until you hit those ambiguities, which shouldn't happen too often.  Any thoughts on the best way to take it to the masses?<br>
 -MoJo <p>Sentimnet without action is the ruin of the soul. - Edward Abbey</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bdrunkenphilosophy.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jstuartmills>jstuartmills</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Drunken Reporter</span><br>  Posts: 39<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/28/03 3:42:29 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fdrunkenphilosophyfrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Condorcet Voting </span><hr size=1> Here's a (hopefully brief) explanation of how your second choice could possibly hurt your first candidate in a close race:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>drop the weakest (smallest magnitude) defeat, repeating if necessary until one of the candidates is unbeaten.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
If your first choice is ranked lower (Nader), and your second choice is ranked higher in the runnings (Gore), then you've helped bump Nader out of the runnings by making the split between Gore and the other candidates higher. BUT you've also helped Nader more than Gore by giving him am extra vote against everyone else, including Gore.<br>
<br>
Example:<br>
You've voted like this: Nader 1, Gore 2, Bush 3<br>
Total results - an ambiguous vote:<br>
G/B 32   XB/G 20X<br>
N/G 31   XG/N 20X<br>
B/N 30   XN/B 15X<br>
   -You've added one vote to N/G, but you've also added one vote to G/B, keeping the spread between the two elections the same, meaning Gore wins. If you'd have just ranked Nader, and left other slots blank, the race would be even (G/B 31). I'm not sure what they'd do in that situation, but as it stands in this election, Gore wins.<br>
<br>
Of course, this isn't a problem except in the closest races. But say the spread looked like this: <br>
<br>
G/B 32,000 <br>
N/G 31,000. <br>
<br>
If 1,001 people wanted to put down N as their only ranked choice, but didn't realize that NOT doing so would hurt N, then they would have hurt N unknowingly.<br>
<br>
Even with this system, though, they've still had a fair say in the situation, and were responsible for Gore winning the election - a much better choice for them than Bush.<br>
<br>
-Mills <p>&quot;They that can give up essential liberty to obtain a little temporary safety deserve neither liberty nor safety&quot;<br>
