And the more candidates you vote for behind your #1 pick the bigger the victory over them or the smaller the defeat, depending on the rest of the voters.  So ranking more candidates is just as likely to strengthen your candidate's position as it is to weaken it.  The only time you should really be concerned with voting for one candidate and one candidate alone is if you really couldn't stand to see anyone else in office.   <p>Sentimnet without action is the ruin of the soul. - Edward Abbey</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bdrunkenphilosophy.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jstuartmills>jstuartmills</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Drunken Reporter</span><br>  Posts: 49<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/28/03 10:51:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fdrunkenphilosophyfrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Condorcet Voting </span><hr size=1> I agree with you that the chances of this sort of race are extremely slim, as I think I said in my post.<br>
<br>
It is still a valid con to the style of voting, but it's a very small one, as the system would still work as it should in this situation - people would still have a voice in the matter of who their president is, even if their first choice did not win.<br>
<br>
This may be taken as a loss by some, but it's also a partial victory.<br>
<br>
I'm not arguing to throw out this system because of that loophole - on the contrary I think it's a great system; much better than what we currently have.<br>
<br>
But I gaurantee that when we talk about this outside of this board, we'll hear a lot of arguments against it. I'd like to know what some of those potential concerns are and have time to think about them to decide if they're *really* an issue.<br>
<br>
-Mills <p>&quot;They that can give up essential liberty to obtain a little temporary safety deserve neither liberty nor safety&quot;<br>
<br>
-Benjamin Franklin, Historical Review of Pennsylvania, 1759.</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bdrunkenphilosophy.showUserPublicProfile?gid=motherjones>motherjones</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Drunken Philosopher</span><br>  Posts: 39<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/28/03 11:17:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fdrunkenphilosophyfrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Condorcet Voting </span><hr size=1> I think it's a valid con as well, but I think it's very marginal.  And since an ideal election system is <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://electionmethods.org/Arrow.htm" target="top">impossible</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->  there's going to always be some trade off.  The thing to keep in mind is the relative weight of the cons to the pros of any proposed voting system.<br>
<br>
